Parse your date to `OffsetDateTime` instance say givenDate, and than create `OffsetDateTime currDate = new OffsetDateTime();`After that do 

    boolean res = currDate.minusDays(2).isAfter(givenDate);
If your res is true than your given days is earlier (older) than two days before

### steps to perform
- parse the `String` to an `OffsetDateTime`
- get the current `OffsetDateTime` with the same offset
- calculate the difference in days using the date only while disregarding the time of day
- check if the result is 2 or older

### code example
```Java
public static void main(String[] args) {
	// example input
	String givenDate = &quot;2023-05-20T08:32:23.243Z&quot;;
	// parse the String
	OffsetDateTime givenOffsetDateTime = OffsetDateTime.parse(givenDate);
	// get the current date and time in the same zone (UTC)
	OffsetDateTime now = OffsetDateTime.now(ZoneOffset.UTC);
	// calculate the time difference of the dates (disregarding time of day)
	Period period = Period.between(
						givenOffsetDateTime.toLocalDate(),
						now.toLocalDate()
					);
	// print the result including a check for 2 days or older
	System.out.println(
			String.format(&quot;%s is %d days older than %s\nwhich means it is %s days in the past&quot;,
							givenOffsetDateTime.toLocalDate(),
